Communicated by:
ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>

[Overall, these problems seem to be similar to the ones that occurred in Panama or Chiapas, Mexico in 2003, a temporary increase due to a glitch in the eradication program. In the case of Chiapas, Mexico, we know there was a breakdown in the sterile fly technology, so that the flies were no longer firing blanks but in fact were breeding. After some technical adjustments, the program got back on track quickly, which is what I suspect will happen here. If the pressure is kept on the disease by movement control and effective release of sterile flies, this outbreak should be contained.

Surveillance is of the utmost importance, though, to insure that the increased incidence in Panama, and particularly the area near the Darien Gap, does not result in allowing the flies, which lay the screwworm eggs, to retake territories north of the Darien Gap. The Darien Gap has for many years been a key surveillance node monitoring foot and mouth disease in the region. Panama was declared free of active screwworm infestations in 2006.

For more information, see the USDA-APHIS International Services website at http://www.aphis.usda.gov/international_safeguarding/screwworm_3.shtml.

For a map of the Darien Gap area, see the OIE website listed above. - Mod.PC

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: http://healthmap.org/r/1D8S.]
